<div class="page">
 			<h1 class="h1_blue_dark">Drawing Inferences</h1>
		<div style="padding-bottom: 20px; padding-top: 10px;">
            <h1 class="h1_gray">Introduction</h1> 
Most of your courses involve reading texts—course syllabi, handouts, essays, and textbook chapters.  
Even visual media, such as films, are considered “texts” to be read and understood by the viewer.   
But not all of the ideas in a text are stated directly.  You must often “read between the lines” to 
interpret what an author is  saying.  That is, you need to make inferences, and this requires your own 
participation as much as the author’s.  To make reasonable inferences, you not only need to carefully 
observe the details in the text, but you need to contribute your own knowledge and experiences.  But how 
do you know which inferences are “reasonable” and which ones are not?  This workshop will help you make 
reasonable inferences. 

		</div>
           

<!-- wrapper lower section -->
<div style="margin-top: 10px;">
		
